SOME of the residents at Kennedy Road squatter camp in Durban have to start all over again . . . Their shacks were destroyed by a fire on Sunday, and about 1 000 people were left homeless! As a result, many have moved in with relatives and neighbours.Simphiwe Ngcobo (45) said the fire started in one of the shacks and spread quickly to the other shacks.&ldquo;I was asleep when I heard people screaming, and I jumped out of bed and ran outside,&rdquo; he told Daily Sun. &ldquo;I realised I still had a chance to save some of my belongings, so I ran back inside. I managed to grab my shoes and a few clothes.&rdquo; But the rest of his belongings were destroyed in the blaze. &ldquo;We don&rsquo;t know what caused the fire. All we know is that it started in one of the shacks.&rdquo; Some of the residents had started rebuilding.Councillor Hassan Haniff said he had contacted disaster management so that affected people could get food and blankets.&ldquo;We&rsquo;re looking at over 200 shacks being burnt,&rdquo; said Haniff, confirming the number of affected residents. &ldquo;About 1 000 people were left homeless after their shacks caught fire.&rdquo; He said he was told that a child was injured and rushed to hospital after she sustained minor burn injuries.&ldquo;I&rsquo;m glad that there were no fatalities,&rdquo; said Haniff. Lieutenant-Colonel Thulani Zwane confirmed the incident. &ldquo;No injuries were reported, and no case was opened,&rdquo; said Zwane.